  <article class="container-prose prose-editorial cs-body" set:html={`<h3><b>Educational Case Study Disclosure</b></h3><p>This case study is hypothetical and for educational purposes only. Scenarios, borrower profiles, loan terms, interest rates, and outcomes are illustrative examples and do not represent current offers or guaranteed terms.</p><p>For specific details including down payment requirements, closing cost estimates, interest rate details, closing cost breakdowns, payment calculations, cash-to-close estimates, or an official Loan Estimate, it is highly recommended you<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a meeting with one of our licensed mortgage advisors</a>.</p><p><b>Learn more:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/24/">Portfolio loan Reg Z advertising requirements (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB official regulation</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1026">Portfolio loan Reg Z full text and compliance</a> – Electronic Code of Federal Regulations</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/rules-policy/regulations/1026/interp-24/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Official portfolio loan advertising interpretations (§1026.24)</a> – CFPB interpretations</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.ecfr.gov/current/title-12/chapter-X/part-1014" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Portfolio loan MAP Rule (Reg N) mortgage advertising</a> – Mortgage advertising rules</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://www.nmlsconsumeraccess.org/">NMLS Consumer Access – Verify portfolio loan lender licensure</a></li></ul><p>Actual loan terms vary by credit profile, property, occupancy, location, market conditions, and lender guidelines. For current options tailored to you,<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a consultation</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> apply online</a>.</p><p>Ready to explore your options?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor.</p>		
					<h2>How Did Portfolio Loan Financing Make This Unique Property Purchase Possible?</h2>				
		<p>Robert H., a 42-year-old marketing consultant who had built a successful agency serving technology companies throughout South Florida, had been searching for the perfect property to combine his business operations with smart real estate investing. After months of searching, he found an ideal mixed-use building in Fort Lauderdale's emerging Flagler Village neighborhood—a three-story property with commercial retail space on the ground floor and two residential apartment units on the upper floors.</p><p>The property checked every box on Robert's list: the ground floor could house his growing marketing agency's offices, the two residential units would generate rental income to offset the mortgage, the location offered excellent walkability and access to downtown, and the property sat in a rapidly appreciating neighborhood with strong redevelopment momentum. With substantial cash reserves, excellent credit, and strong business income, Robert felt confident he'd secure financing quickly.</p><p>What Robert didn't anticipate was that virtually every conventional lender would immediately reject his mixed-use property purchase—not because of his financial qualifications, but because the property itself didn't fit the rigid boxes that Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac require. His perfect property, his solid finances, and his smart investment strategy didn't matter when the property type automatically disqualified him from conventional financing.</p><p>Facing similar challenges?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to explore your options.</p><h2><b>The Challenge: Why Traditional Lenders Rejected This Mixed-Use Property Purchase</b></h2><p>Robert submitted applications to four conventional mortgage lenders and three major banks, confident that his strong financial profile would easily secure approval. Every single lender rejected his application within days—some within hours.</p><h3><b>Why Do Traditional Lenders Refuse Portfolio Loan Financing for Mixed-Use Properties?</b></h3><p>Traditional mortgage lenders operate within strict Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac guidelines that define exactly what property types qualify for conventional residential financing. Mixed-use properties—buildings combining commercial and residential space—create immediate complications for conventional underwriting.</p><p>Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac have specific rules about mixed-use properties that severely limit financing options. The residential portion must represent a certain proportion of the total property, the commercial use can't exceed certain thresholds, specific commercial uses are prohibited, and even when properties technically qualify on paper, many lenders reject them entirely to avoid complexity.</p><h3><b>What Made Robert's Property Ineligible for Conventional Financing?</b></h3><p>Robert's target property faced multiple conventional financing obstacles:</p><p><b>Property configuration challenges:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Mixed-use building with ground floor commercial and upper floor residential</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Commercial space represented substantial portion of total square footage</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Owner-occupied commercial use (Robert's office) combined with rental residential units</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Three separate "uses" in one building (owner business + two rental units)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Property didn't fit clean residential or commercial financing categories</li></ul><p><b>Underwriting complexity:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Lenders couldn't determine if property should be residential or commercial loan</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Income from multiple sources (business operations, rental units, owner use)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Commercial space valuation differs from residential unit valuation</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Mixed-use appraisals require specialized expertise many lenders avoid</li></ul><p>"Every lender told me essentially the same thing," Robert explained. "Your finances look great, your down payment is substantial, your credit is excellent—but we can't finance this property type. It's mixed-use, and we only do residential mortgages or commercial mortgages, not properties that combine both. Try a commercial lender instead."</p><h3><b>Why Couldn't Commercial Lenders Help Robert?</b></h3><p>Robert followed the advice and contacted several commercial real estate lenders. Those conversations proved equally frustrating but for different reasons:</p><p><b>Commercial lender limitations:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Minimum loan amounts far exceeded Robert's purchase price</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Required extensive commercial real estate investment track record</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Focused on larger commercial properties, not small mixed-use buildings</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Offered only short-term commercial loans, not long-term fixed residential-style financing</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Higher interest rates and more expensive terms than residential mortgages</li></ul><p>"Commercial lenders treated my property as too small and too residential," Robert said. "They wanted to finance large apartment buildings or office complexes, not a three-story mixed-use building where the owner occupies part of it. I was stuck in a no-man's land—too commercial for residential lenders, too residential for commercial lenders."</p><h3><b>How Did Conventional Lending Limitations Threaten Robert's Investment Strategy?</b></h3><p>Without financing options, Robert faced losing the property to other buyers who might have cash or alternative financing. The building represented the perfect combination of business location, investment income, and appreciation potential—exactly the type of asset that would build long-term wealth while supporting his business operations.</p><p>"This property would generate rental income while I used the first floor for my agency," Robert explained. "The two residential units would cash flow positively even after covering the full mortgage payment, property taxes, and insurance. I'd essentially work in a building that pays for itself through rental income and appreciates in a rapidly growing neighborhood. But I couldn't access conventional financing because the property didn't fit Fannie Mae's neat little boxes."</p><p>The property was under contract with a deadline approaching. Without securing financing soon, Robert would lose his earnest money deposit and miss the investment opportunity he'd been planning toward for months.</p><p>Experiencing similar rejection?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> to discuss alternative qualification methods.</p><h2><b>The Discovery: How Robert Found Portfolio Loan Solutions</b></h2><p>Robert discovered<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/portfolio-loan/"> portfolio loan</a> financing through his commercial real estate attorney who had worked with clients in similar situations. The attorney explained that portfolio lenders keep loans on their own books rather than selling them to Fannie Mae or Freddie Mac, giving them flexibility to finance properties that don't meet conventional guidelines.</p><p>"My attorney said portfolio lenders can make their own rules because they're not constrained by Fannie Mae underwriting boxes," Robert said. "They can look at the actual property, the actual borrower, and the actual situation rather than just checking boxes on a conventional checklist. That sounded exactly like what I needed."</p><h3><b>What Makes Portfolio Loan Financing Different from Traditional Mortgages?</b></h3><p>The portfolio loan advisor explained that portfolio lenders operate fundamentally differently from conventional mortgage lenders. While traditional lenders must follow rigid Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac guidelines because they sell loans to those entities, portfolio lenders hold loans in their own investment portfolios—giving them complete underwriting flexibility.</p><p>Portfolio loan financing accepts property types conventional lenders automatically reject, including mixed-use buildings, unique properties, non-warrantable condos, properties with commercial components, and properties that don't fit standard residential categories. These lenders evaluate the borrower's complete financial picture, the property's actual value and income potential, and the overall investment merit rather than just checking conventional guideline boxes.</p><h3><b>How Do Portfolio Lenders Evaluate Mixed-Use Property Purchases?</b></h3><p>"The portfolio lender conversation felt completely different from conventional lenders," Robert explained. "Instead of saying 'we can't do mixed-use properties,' the advisor asked about the property's income potential, my business stability, the neighborhood growth trajectory, and my long-term plans. They wanted to understand the complete investment picture rather than just eliminating me because of property type."</p><p>The advisor outlined how portfolio loan financing could work for Robert's mixed-use property purchase:</p><p><b>Portfolio lender evaluation approach:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Assess total property value including both commercial and residential components</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Evaluate rental income from residential units</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Consider business stability and Robert's income from marketing agency</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Review neighborhood appreciation trends and property investment merit</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Analyze Robert's complete financial picture including reserves and other assets</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Underwrite based on actual debt service coverage and investment feasibility</li></ul><p>For the first time since starting his search for financing, Robert felt confident he could actually purchase the property that perfectly fit his business and investment strategy.</p><h2><b>The Solution: Portfolio Loan Approval and Closing Process</b></h2><p>Robert worked with his portfolio loan advisor to assemble comprehensive documentation that told the complete story of his financial strength and the property's investment merit.</p><h3><b>What Documentation Did Robert Provide for Portfolio Loan Approval?</b></h3><p>Portfolio lenders require thorough documentation but focus on telling the complete financial story rather than just checking boxes:</p><p><b>Property documentation:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Purchase contract with detailed property description</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Mixed-use property appraisal by experienced commercial/residential appraiser</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Current rent roll showing existing tenant leases</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Property income and expense statements</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Comparable sales analysis for mixed-use properties in area</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Property inspection reports</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Zoning verification confirming legal mixed-use status</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Future rent projections for residential units</li></ul><p><b>Business documentation:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Tax returns from marketing agency showing consistent strong revenue</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Business bank statements demonstrating healthy cash flow</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Profit and loss statements showing business profitability</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Client contracts and revenue pipeline demonstrating business stability</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Business plan for occupying ground floor commercial space</li></ul><p><b>Personal financial documentation:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Personal tax returns showing strong income</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Personal bank statements with substantial reserves</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Credit reports showing excellent credit score</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Documentation of liquid assets and investment accounts</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Statement of other real estate owned (if applicable)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Proof of appropriate down payment funds</li></ul><p><b>Investment analysis:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Detailed proforma showing projected income and expenses</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Cash flow analysis demonstrating positive debt service coverage</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Neighborhood market analysis showing appreciation trends</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Renovation budget if improvements planned</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Exit strategy or long-term hold plan</li></ul><p>"The portfolio lender wanted to see everything," Robert said. "But unlike conventional lenders who were looking for reasons to say no, the portfolio lender was building a complete picture to understand why this was a smart investment. Every document I provided strengthened my case rather than creating new obstacles."</p><h3><b>How Long Does Portfolio Loan Approval Take?</b></h3><p>The portfolio lender moved efficiently through Robert's application, though more slowly than conventional mortgages due to the unique property type requiring specialized evaluation:</p><ol><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Initial consultation</b> - Reviewed property type and borrower qualifications (Day 1)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Preliminary approval</b> - Confirmed portfolio loan could work for mixed-use property (Day 3)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Document submission</b> - Uploaded complete financial and property documentation (Day 5-7)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Property evaluation</b> - Lender analyzed mixed-use property value and income (Day 8-14)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Underwriting review</b> - Comprehensive analysis of borrower finances and property merit (Day 15-21)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Specialized appraisal</b> - Mixed-use appraisal by qualified appraiser (Day 10-25)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Conditional approval</b> - Approved pending final documentation verification (Day 28)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Clear to close</b> - Final approval issued with all conditions satisfied (Day 35)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Closing</b> - Successfully funded and closed (Day 42)</li></ol><h3><b>What Terms Did the Portfolio Loan Provide?</b></h3><p>Robert secured favorable portfolio loan terms that reflected both his strong financial profile and the property's solid investment fundamentals:</p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Conservative loan-to-value ratio</b> appropriate for mixed-use property</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Competitive interest rate</b> for portfolio loan financing on unique property type</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Long-term fixed-rate structure</b> providing payment stability over decades</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Appropriate down payment</b> for mixed-use investment property</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>No prepayment penalties</b> allowing flexibility for future refinancing</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Standard amortization</b> with predictable principal reduction over time</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Flexible underwriting</b> accommodating the property's unique characteristics</li></ul><p>"The portfolio loan terms were excellent considering the property type," Robert explained. "The rate was competitive, the structure was exactly what I needed for long-term ownership, and the underwriting flexibility meant I could actually buy the property I wanted rather than settling for something that fit conventional financing boxes."</p><p>Ready to purchase?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/purchase-inquiry/"> Submit a purchase inquiry</a> to discuss your scenario.</p><h2><b>The Results: Mixed-Use Property Acquired and Performing Excellently</b></h2><p>Robert closed on his mixed-use property approximately six weeks after starting the portfolio loan application process. The transaction delivered exactly the combined business location and investment property he had envisioned.</p><h3><b>What Results Did Robert Achieve with Portfolio Loan Financing?</b></h3><p><b>Final purchase outcome:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Successfully acquired mixed-use property in appreciating Fort Lauderdale neighborhood</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Conservative loan-to-value ratio leaving substantial equity cushion</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Competitive interest rate for portfolio loan on unique property</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Long-term fixed-rate providing payment predictability</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Timeline:</b> Application to closing in 42 days</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Property:</b> Three-story mixed-use building, Flagler Village, Fort Lauderdale, FL</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Configuration:</b> Ground floor commercial (owner-occupied) + two residential rental units</li></ul><p><b>Property performance after purchase:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Relocated marketing agency to ground floor commercial space</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Leased both residential units to quality tenants immediately</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Rental income from two units covers substantial portion of total mortgage payment</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Property generating positive cash flow after all expenses</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Neighborhood appreciation continuing as predicted</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Building substantial equity through both principal paydown and market appreciation</li></ul><h3><b>How Did Portfolio Loan Financing Compare to Conventional Lending?</b></h3><p><b>Traditional lender attempts vs. portfolio loan:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Traditional lender qualification:</b> Rejected by all seven lenders contacted</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Portfolio lender qualification:</b> Approved with favorable terms</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Property type flexibility:</b> Traditional rejected mixed-use; portfolio accepted and understood it</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Underwriting approach:</b> Traditional checked boxes; portfolio evaluated complete picture</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Financing achieved:</b> Portfolio loan made purchase possible</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Investment strategy:</b> ACHIEVED ✓</li></ul><p>"The portfolio loan made possible something that would have been impossible with conventional financing," Robert said. "I'm now working in a building I own, generating rental income that covers most of my mortgage payment, building equity in an appreciating neighborhood, and positioning myself for long-term wealth creation. The property serves both my immediate business needs and my long-term investment strategy—exactly what I envisioned but couldn't access through traditional lending."</p><h3><b>What Are Robert's Next Steps After Successful Portfolio Loan Purchase?</b></h3><p>Robert views the mixed-use property purchase as the foundation of a broader real estate investment strategy. The two residential units generate strong cash flow, the commercial space houses his growing agency rent-free (saving substantial business expenses), and the property appreciates in Fort Lauderdale's redeveloping urban core.</p><p>"My goal is to acquire three to five investment properties over the next decade," Robert said. "This mixed-use building is property #1—combining my business operations with rental income and appreciation potential. Properties #2 through #5 will be traditional rental properties in strong appreciation markets, building a diversified portfolio that generates passive income and long-term wealth."</p><p>When Robert is ready to acquire additional properties, he plans to potentially use a<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/heloc/"> HELOC</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/home-equity-loan/"> Home Equity Loan</a> on his mixed-use property to access equity for down payments without refinancing and losing his current favorable rate structure. He's also considering portfolio loans for future acquisitions if he identifies other unique properties that don't fit conventional financing molds.</p><p>"The portfolio loan experience taught me that creative real estate investing often requires creative financing," Robert reflected. "The best investment opportunities sometimes don't fit neat conventional boxes. Portfolio lenders understand that and provide financing solutions for properties and situations that make investment sense even when they don't check Fannie Mae's boxes. Now I'm building wealth through real estate while operating my business in a building that pays for itself. That's the power of portfolio loan flexibility."</p><p>Ready to get started?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/same-day-approval/"> Get approved</a> or<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> schedule a call</a> to discuss your situation.</p><h2><b>Exploring Other Portfolio Loan Options?</b></h2><p>While Robert used portfolio loan financing to purchase a mixed-use property, portfolio loans work for multiple unique situations:</p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Own multiple properties? See how an<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/portfolio-loan-refinance/"> investor used portfolio loan to consolidate multiple mortgages</a></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1">Unique property type? Learn how portfolio loans<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/portfolio-loan-unique-property"> finance properties conventional lenders reject</a></li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> to find success stories matching your situation</li></ul><h2><b>Key Takeaways for Buyers of Unique Properties</b></h2><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Portfolio loan financing accepts property types conventional lenders automatically reject</b>—mixed-use properties, unique configurations, non-warrantable condos, properties with commercial components, and properties outside standard residential categories can all qualify when lenders keep loans in their own portfolios rather than selling to Fannie Mae or Freddie Mac (<a href="https://www.fanniemae.com/">Fannie Mae property eligibility guidelines</a>)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Portfolio lenders evaluate complete financial pictures rather than just checking boxes</b>—these lenders assess borrower financial strength, property investment merit, income potential, and overall feasibility rather than automatically disqualifying borrowers based on property type or situation characteristics (<a href="https://www.consumerfinance.gov/">Understanding portfolio lending</a>)</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Mixed-use properties require specialized appraisals and underwriting</b>—properties combining commercial and residential uses need appraisers experienced in both property types and lenders comfortable analyzing income from multiple sources and uses</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Strong financial profiles unlock better portfolio loan terms</b>—while portfolio lenders offer flexibility on property types, excellent credit, substantial reserves, appropriate down payments, and strong income still significantly improve interest rates and loan structures</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><b>Think strategically about property types and investment opportunities</b>—the best investment properties sometimes don't fit conventional financing categories, but portfolio loans provide access to unique opportunities that can build substantial wealth when acquired at appropriate valuations in strong markets</li></ul><p>Have questions about portfolio loan financing for unique properties?<a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/schedule-call/"> Schedule a call</a> with a loan advisor today.</p><h2><b>Alternative Loan Programs for Unique Property Purchases</b></h2><p>If portfolio loan isn't the perfect fit, consider these alternatives:</p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/non-qm-loan/">Non-QM Loan</a> – Flexible qualifying for non-traditional borrowers</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/commercial-real-estate-loans">Commercial Real Estate Loan</a> – Financing for larger commercial properties</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/dscr-loan/">DSCR Loan</a> – Qualify based on property cash flow for investment properties</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/bank-statement-loan/">Bank Statement Loan</a> – Alternative income documentation for self-employed borrowers</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/asset-based-loan/">Asset-Based Loan</a> – Qualify using liquid assets rather than income</li></ul><p><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/">Explore all loan programs</a> to find your best financing solution.</p><h2><b>Helpful Portfolio Loan Resources</b></h2><p><b>Learn more about this loan program:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-programs/portfolio-loan/">Complete Portfolio Loan Guide</a> - Detailed requirements, rates, and qualification guidelines</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/loan-calculator/portfolio-loan-calculator">Portfolio Loan Calculator</a> - Estimate your potential financing</li></ul><p><b>Similar success stories:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/portfolio-loan-refinance/">How an investor consolidated multiple properties with portfolio loan refinance</a> - Portfolio consolidation success</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/portfolio-loan-unique-property">Business owner purchases unique property with portfolio financing</a> - Non-standard property approval</li><li style="font-weight: 400;" aria-level="1"><a href="https://stairwaymortgage.com/case-studies/">View all case studies</a> - Browse by your investment stage</li></ul><p><b>External authoritative resources:</b></p><ul><li style="font-weight: 400;" ari